definition.value: A person who is the victim of genocide. A person who is killed or dies as the result of genocide.
A person who was killed during or who died as a result of the Holocaust.
A person who has been murdered.
A person who has committed suicide.
The systematic mistreatment of an individual or group of individuals as a response to their being gay men.
The systematic mistreatment of an individual or group of individuals as a response to their being lesbians.
The systematic mistreatment of an individual or group of individuals as a response to their being bisexual.
The systematic mistreatment of an individual or group of individuals as a response to their being transgender.
The systematic mistreatment of an individual or group of individuals as a response to their being intersex.
The systematic mistreatment of an individual or group of individuals as a response to their being asexual.
A periodical publication intended to further the progress of science, usually by reporting new research.
Any of various journals which communicate academic study and research in the humanities.

A peer-reviewed scientific journal that communicates medical information to physicians and other health professionals. Journals that cover many medical specialties are sometimes called general medical journals.
Medical journals which cover endocrinological topics.
Medical journals which cover pediatric topics.
Scientific journals which cover disciplines falling under the natural sciences.
Scientific journals which cover disciplines falling under the social sciences.
Scientific journals which cover anthropological topics.
Scientific journals which cover archaeological topics.
Medical journals which cover psychiatric topics.
Scientific journals which cover psychological topics.
Scientific journals which cover political science topics.
Scientific journals which cover sexological topics.
Academic journals which cover law topics.
Scientific journals which cover educational topics.
Medical journals which cover gynecological topics.
Scientific journals which cover history topics.
Medical journals which cover gerontological topics.
Academic journals which cover gender studies topics.
Academic journals which cover women's studies topics.
Academic journals which cover linguistics topics.
Scientific journals which cover biological topics.
Medical journals which cover surgical topics.
Medical journals which cover radiological topics.
Medical journals which cover cardiological topics.
A classification system used to transform descriptions of medical diagnoses or procedures into standardized statistical code in a process known as clinical coding.

An organization dedicated to furthering a particular social cause or advocating for a shared point of view. In economic terms, it is an organization that uses its surplus of the revenues to further achieve its ultimate objective, rather than distributing its income to the organization's shareholders, leaders, or members.
Non-profit organizations concerned with various aspects of health, e.g., education, promotion, treatment, services, etc.
An increase in social acceptance conditional upon concealing one's status as being transgender; i.e. being "read" as cisgender.
Note that perception of being cisgender as a distinct privilege is not universally agreed upon.
Institutions which provide educational services.
An institution of secondary education, higher learning, research, or honorary membership.
A national institution of secondary education, higher learning, research, or honorary membership.
An international institution of secondary education, higher learning, research, or honorary membership.
A scientific institution of secondary education, higher learning, research, or honorary membership.
An art institution of secondary education, higher learning, research, or honorary membership.
A sexological institution of secondary education, higher learning, research, or honorary membership.
An organization which aims to further a particular profession, the interests of individuals engaged in that profession, and the public interest.

A trade association that brings together practitioners of a particular geographical area (a country, region, province). In common-law countries, they are often grouped by medical specialties (cardiologists, family doctors, etc.).
Professional associations formed of and for psychiatrists.
Professional associations formed of and for psychologists.
